        {
          "title": "Sensors, Perception & 3D Understanding",
          "slug": "sensors-perception-3d",
          "order_index": 1,
          "content": "# Sensors, Perception & 3D Understanding\n\nBefore a robot can act intelligently, it must perceive the world. Unlike humans, who effortlessly fuse vision, touch, and proprioception into a coherent 3D understanding, robots rely on an array of engineered sensors — each with distinct strengths and failure modes.\n\n## Camera Systems\n\n**RGB cameras** are the cheapest and most information-dense sensor. A single frame contains color, texture, and implicit depth cues. Modern vision models can extract objects, semantics, and even rough geometry from monocular images.\n\n**Stereo cameras** use two lenses at a known separation (baseline) to compute **disparity maps** — the pixel-level shift between left and right views — which are then converted to depth. Accuracy degrades with distance and fails on textureless surfaces.\n\n**Depth cameras** (e.g., Intel RealSense, Azure Kinect) project structured infrared light patterns and measure deformation to compute depth directly. They work well indoors at short range (0.3–10 m) but struggle in sunlight.\n\n## LiDAR\n\n**LiDAR** (Light Detection and Ranging) fires laser pulses and measures return time to compute precise 3D distances. A spinning LiDAR sensor produces a **point cloud** — a set of (x, y, z) coordinates — with centimeter-level accuracy at ranges up to 200 m.\n\n| Sensor | Range | Accuracy | Cost | Conditions |\n|--------|-------|----------|------|------------|\n| RGB Camera | Unlimited | No direct depth | Low | Lighting dependent |\n| Stereo Camera | 0.5–30 m | ~1 cm at 2 m | Medium | Texture dependent |\n| Depth Camera | 0.3–10 m | ~1 mm at 1 m | Medium | Indoor only |\n| LiDAR | 1–200 m | ~2 cm | High | All weather |\n\n## Other Sensors\n\n- **IMUs** (Inertial Measurement Units): Accelerometers + gyroscopes measure linear acceleration and angular velocity. Essential for pose estimation and state tracking.\n- **Force/torque sensors**: Measure contact forces at the wrist or fingertip. Critical for assembly tasks where force control matters.\n- **Tactile sensors**: Arrays of pressure-sensitive elements (e.g., GelSight) that measure contact geometry and force distribution at millimeter resolution.\n\n## Sensor Fusion\n\nNo single sensor is sufficient. **Sensor fusion** combines complementary modalities:\n\n- Camera + LiDAR: dense color + accurate geometry (common in self-driving)\n- IMU + Camera: **Visual-Inertial Odometry (VIO)** for real-time pose tracking\n- Force + Vision: detecting contact events and adjusting grasp pressure\n\nFusion approaches range from simple calibration and projection (painting LiDAR points onto camera images) to learned multimodal encoders that jointly reason over all streams.\n\n## 3D Representations\n\nOnce raw sensor data is captured, it must be converted into a useful 3D representation:\n\n- **Point clouds**: Raw 3D points — lightweight, unstructured, processed by networks like PointNet\n- **Voxels**: 3D grid cells — structured but memory-intensive (O(n³))\n- **Meshes**: Triangle surfaces — compact, standard in graphics, hard to learn directly\n- **NeRFs** (Neural Radiance Fields): Implicit neural representations that encode a scene as a continuous function mapping 3D coordinates → color and density\n- **3D Gaussian Splatting**: Represents scenes as collections of 3D Gaussians — faster rendering than NeRFs with comparable quality\n\nThese representations are used downstream for object detection, grasp planning, navigation, and scene understanding.\n\n## Key Takeaways\n\n- Robots perceive the world through cameras, LiDAR, IMUs, and tactile sensors\n- Each sensor has distinct tradeoffs in range, accuracy, cost, and conditions\n- Sensor fusion combines modalities for robust perception\n- 3D representations (point clouds, NeRFs, Gaussian splatting) encode the world for downstream reasoning\n\n## Recommended Reading\n\n- [NeRF: Representing Scenes as Neural Radiance Fields for View Synthesis](https://www.matthewtancik.com/nerf) — The original NeRF project page with interactive demos and paper links.\n",
          "summary": "Robots perceive the world through cameras, LiDAR, IMUs, and tactile sensors, fusing multiple modalities into 3D representations like point clouds, NeRFs, and Gaussian splatting for downstream reasoning and control.",
