        {
          "title": "Reinforcement Learning for Robotics",
          "slug": "reinforcement-learning-robotics",
          "order_index": 0,
          "content": "# Reinforcement Learning for Robotics\n\nReinforcement learning (RL) teaches robots by letting them **learn from trial and error**. Instead of programming explicit rules for every situation, the robot explores its environment, takes actions, receives rewards (or penalties), and gradually discovers behavior that maximizes long-term success.\n\n## The RL Framework\n\nAn RL problem is defined by:\n\n- **State (s)**: What the robot currently observes (joint angles, camera image, object positions)\n- **Action (a)**: What the robot does (joint torques, gripper commands, wheel velocities)\n- **Reward (r)**: A scalar signal indicating how good the outcome is\n- **Policy (π)**: A function mapping states to actions — the \"brain\" of the robot\n- **Value function (V)**: The expected total future reward from a state\n\nThe goal is to find the policy π* that maximizes the expected cumulative reward:\n\n```\nπ* = argmax_π E[Σ γᵗ rₜ]\n```\n\nwhere **γ** (gamma) is the discount factor, typically 0.99, making the agent prefer sooner rewards.\n\n## Policy Gradient Methods\n\nFor robotics, actions are continuous (joint torques are real numbers, not discrete choices). **Policy gradient** methods directly optimize a parameterized policy:\n\n- **PPO (Proximal Policy Optimization)**: The workhorse of robot RL. Clips policy updates to prevent catastrophically large changes. Stable, parallelizable, and effective across locomotion and manipulation.\n\n- **SAC (Soft Actor-Critic)**: Maximizes reward while also maximizing entropy (action randomness). This encourages exploration and produces robust policies. Excellent for dexterous manipulation.\n\n| Algorithm | Type | Strengths | Typical Use |\n|-----------|------|-----------|-------------|\n| **PPO** | On-policy | Stable, easy to tune | Locomotion, general tasks |\n| **SAC** | Off-policy | Sample-efficient, exploratory | Manipulation, dexterous control |\n| **TD3** | Off-policy | Handles overestimation bias | Continuous control benchmarks |\n\n## Reward Shaping\n\nDesigning reward functions is one of the hardest parts of robot RL. Sparse rewards (\"1 if task is complete, 0 otherwise\") are principled but make learning nearly impossible — the robot may never stumble upon success.\n\n**Reward shaping** adds intermediate signals to guide learning:\n\n- Distance to target (closer = higher reward)\n- Alignment of gripper with grasp pose\n- Penalizing excessive force or energy\n- Curriculum of increasingly difficult goals\n\nThe danger is **reward hacking**: the robot finds unintended shortcuts that maximize reward without solving the real task.\n\n## Locomotion\n\nTeaching robots to walk is a flagship RL application. The policy maps proprioceptive state (joint positions, velocities, body orientation from IMU) to joint torques:\n\n- **Quadruped locomotion**: ANYmal, Spot — RL policies that walk, run, climb stairs, and recover from pushes\n- **Bipedal walking**: Humanoid balance is inherently unstable; RL learns robust gaits that traditional controllers struggle to achieve\n- **Terrain adaptation**: Policies trained with domain randomization generalize to rocky, slippery, and uneven surfaces\n\n## Manipulation\n\nManipulation tasks — grasping, placing, inserting, pushing — present different challenges:\n\n- **Contact-rich**: The policy must reason about forces and friction\n- **Precision**: Millimeter-level accuracy for assembly tasks\n- **Multi-step**: Long-horizon tasks require planning and sequencing\n\n## Key Takeaways\n\n- RL lets robots learn through trial and error rather than manual programming\n- PPO and SAC are the dominant algorithms for continuous robot control\n- Reward design is critical — sparse rewards are principled but impractical; shaped rewards risk hacking\n- RL has achieved remarkable results in both locomotion and manipulation\n\n## Recommended Reading\n\n- [Deep Reinforcement Learning](https://lilianweng.github.io/posts/2018-02-19-rl-overview/) by Lilian Weng — A comprehensive overview of deep RL algorithms including policy gradient methods.\n",
          "summary": "Reinforcement learning teaches robots through trial and error using policy gradient algorithms like PPO and SAC, with carefully shaped rewards guiding learning for locomotion and manipulation tasks.",
          "concepts": [
            "reinforcement learning",
            "PPO",
            "SAC",
            "reward shaping",
            "policy gradient",
            "locomotion",
            "manipulation"
          ],
          "youtube_id": null,
          "video_title": null,
          "vimeo_url": null,
          "transcript": null
