        {
          "title": "Imitation Learning & Demonstrations",
          "slug": "imitation-learning-demonstrations",
          "order_index": 1,
          "content": "# Imitation Learning & Demonstrations\n\nRL requires a reward function, and designing good rewards is hard. **Imitation learning** sidesteps this problem entirely: instead of specifying what success looks like mathematically, you simply show the robot what to do.\n\n## Learning from Demonstrations\n\nThe core idea: collect demonstrations of a human (or expert policy) performing a task, then train a policy to reproduce that behavior. No reward function required — the demonstrations *are* the specification.\n\nThis is particularly valuable for tasks where:\n\n- The reward is hard to define (\"fold the laundry neatly\")\n- Safety constraints make random exploration dangerous\n- Expert knowledge is available but hard to formalize\n\n## Behavior Cloning\n\n**Behavior cloning (BC)** is the simplest form of imitation learning: treat it as supervised learning on (state, action) pairs from expert demonstrations.\n\n```python\ndataset = [(s₁, a₁), (s₂, a₂), ..., (sₙ, aₙ)]  # expert trajectories\npolicy = train_supervised(dataset)  # minimize ||π(s) - a||²\n```\n\nBC is simple and effective when you have enough data, but suffers from **distribution shift**: the policy encounters states during deployment that differ from the expert's trajectory, and small errors compound over time.\n\n## DAgger: Dataset Aggregation\n\n**DAgger** (Dataset Aggregation) addresses distribution shift through interactive learning:\n\n1. Train an initial policy π from expert demonstrations\n2. Roll out π in the environment, collecting new states\n3. Query the expert for the correct action at each new state\n4. Add these (state, action) pairs to the dataset\n5. Retrain and repeat\n\nBy exposing the expert to the learner's actual state distribution, DAgger eliminates compounding errors. The cost is that it requires an interactive expert — the human must be available to label the robot's mistakes.\n\n## Inverse Reinforcement Learning\n\n**Inverse RL (IRL)** takes a different approach: instead of copying actions directly, it infers the underlying **reward function** from demonstrations, then optimizes a policy against that learned reward.\n\nThe insight is that demonstrations implicitly encode what the expert values. If you can recover the reward, you can train a policy that generalizes better than behavior cloning — it understands *why* the expert acted that way, not just *what* they did.\n\nKey IRL algorithms:\n- **Maximum Entropy IRL**: Assumes the expert is noisily optimal; finds rewards that make demonstrations most probable\n- **GAIL (Generative Adversarial Imitation Learning)**: Uses a discriminator to distinguish expert from learner behavior, effectively learning a reward signal adversarially\n\n## Data Collection Methods\n\nThe quality and scale of demonstrations directly determine learning success:\n\n| Method | Pros | Cons |\n|--------|------|------|\n| **Kinesthetic teaching** | Intuitive, no special hardware | Limited to compliant robots, slow |\n| **Teleoperation (gamepad)** | Cheap, accessible | Low-dimensional, imprecise |\n| **VR controllers** | 6-DoF control, natural hand tracking | Requires VR setup, embodiment gap |\n| **Exoskeletons** | Direct joint-to-joint mapping | Expensive, heavy |\n| **Video demonstrations** | Massive scale (YouTube, etc.) | No action labels, viewpoint mismatch |\n\n**Teleoperation** with VR controllers has emerged as the sweet spot: operators use hand-tracking controllers to manipulate a robot in real time, producing high-quality demonstrations at reasonable cost.\n\n## Key Takeaways\n\n- Imitation learning trains policies from expert demonstrations rather than reward functions\n- Behavior cloning is simple but suffers from distribution shift\n- DAgger fixes distribution shift through interactive expert queries\n- Inverse RL recovers the underlying reward function for better generalization\n- VR teleoperation is the current best practice for high-quality demonstration collection\n",
          "summary": "Imitation learning trains robot policies from expert demonstrations rather than reward functions, using techniques like behavior cloning, DAgger for interactive correction, and inverse RL to infer underlying goals from observed behavior.",
          "concepts": [
            "imitation learning",
            "behavior cloning",
            "DAgger",
            "inverse reinforcement learning",
            "teleoperation",
            "distribution shift",
            "GAIL"
          ],
          "youtube_id": null,
