    {
      "title": "Foundation Models for Robotics",
      "order_index": 3,
      "lessons": [
        {
          "title": "Vision-Language-Action Models",
          "slug": "vision-language-action-models",
          "order_index": 0,
          "content": "# Vision-Language-Action Models\n\nThe most exciting frontier in physical AI is the convergence of **language understanding** and **robot control**. Vision-Language-Action (VLA) models take a camera image and a natural language instruction as input and directly output robot actions — no hand-crafted state machines, no task-specific reward functions.\n\n## The VLA Paradigm\n\nA **VLA model** unifies three modalities in a single architecture:\n\n- **Vision**: Camera image(s) of the scene\n- **Language**: A natural language instruction (\"pick up the red cup\")\n- **Action**: Robot motor commands (end-effector position, gripper open/close)\n\nThe architecture typically builds on a pre-trained **vision-language model** (like PaLM-E or LLaVA) and adds an action output head. The key innovation is treating robot actions as just another output modality — like generating text, but generating motor commands instead.\n\n## RT-1: Robotics Transformer\n\n**RT-1** (Robotics Transformer 1) by Google DeepMind was the first large-scale demonstration of this approach:\n\n- Trained on 130,000 real robot demonstrations across 700+ tasks\n- Architecture: Image tokenizer + language tokens → Transformer → discretized actions\n- Actions tokenized into 256 bins per dimension (position, rotation, gripper)\n- Achieved 97% success rate on seen tasks, 76% on unseen tasks\n\nThe key insight from RT-1: **scale matters**. More data, more tasks, and a larger model dramatically improved generalization.\n\n## RT-2: Vision-Language-Action Model\n\n**RT-2** took the next logical step: fine-tune a pre-trained **vision-language model** (PaLI-X, 55B parameters) to output robot actions directly.\n\n- Robot actions are represented as text tokens: \"1 128 91 241 5 101 127\"\n- The model co-trains on web-scale vision-language data AND robot demonstrations\n- Result: emergent capabilities — the robot can follow instructions involving concepts never seen in robot data (\"move the banana to the country that has a flag with this color\")\n\nRT-2 demonstrated that **web knowledge transfers to robot control**: a model that knows what a \"Taylor Swift poster\" looks like (from web data) can pick one up (using robot data).\n\n## SayCan: Grounding Language in Affordances\n\n**SayCan** addresses a different problem: language models know many things, but not what a specific robot can physically do right now.\n\nSayCan combines:\n- **\"Say\"**: An LLM generates candidate actions in natural language\n- **\"Can\"**: A learned affordance model scores each action by how likely the robot can execute it successfully in the current scene\n\nFor example, given \"I'm hungry,\" the LLM might suggest \"go to the kitchen, open the fridge, grab an apple.\" The affordance model filters this to actions the robot can actually perform given its current position, available objects, and capabilities.\n\n## Open-Vocabulary Manipulation\n\nTraditional robot systems can only handle objects they were explicitly trained on. VLA models enable **open-vocabulary manipulation**: robots that understand novel instructions about novel objects.\n\nThis is powered by the vision-language backbone's understanding of the visual world — learned from billions of image-text pairs on the internet — combined with robot action training.\n\n## Key Takeaways\n\n- VLA models unify vision, language, and robot actions in a single architecture\n- RT-1 showed that data scale enables generalization across tasks\n- RT-2 demonstrated that web knowledge transfers to robot control\n- SayCan grounds language model suggestions in physical affordances\n- Open-vocabulary manipulation enables robots to handle novel instructions and objects\n\n## Recommended Reading\n\n- [RT-2: Vision-Language-Action Models Transfer Web Knowledge to Robotic Control](https://robotics-transformer2.github.io/) — Project page for RT-2 with demos, paper, and detailed results on vision-language-action transfer.\n",
          "summary": "Vision-Language-Action models unify camera images, natural language instructions, and robot motor commands in a single architecture, with models like RT-2 demonstrating that web-scale knowledge can transfer directly to robot control.",
          "concepts": [
            "VLA models",
            "RT-1",
            "RT-2",
            "SayCan",
            "open-vocabulary manipulation",
