        {
          "title": "Manipulation & Dexterous Control",
          "slug": "manipulation-dexterous-control",
          "order_index": 1,
          "content": "# Manipulation & Dexterous Control\n\nPicking up a coffee mug seems trivial to humans, but it requires solving a cascade of problems: detecting the mug, planning a collision-free approach, choosing a stable grasp, controlling contact forces, and adapting if the mug slips. **Dexterous manipulation** — using multi-fingered hands for complex object interactions — is one of the hardest open problems in robotics.\n\n## From Simple Grasping to Dexterous Manipulation\n\nManipulation capabilities exist on a spectrum:\n\n| Level | Description | Example |\n|-------|-------------|--------|\n| **Parallel-jaw grasping** | Two-finger pinch grasp | Pick up a box from a bin |\n| **Multi-grasp planning** | Choose among multiple grasp types | Select power vs precision grasp |\n| **Sequential manipulation** | Multi-step object rearrangement | Pack items into a box |\n| **Dexterous manipulation** | Multi-finger, contact-rich control | Rotate a pen between fingers |\n| **Tool use** | Use objects as tools | Use a spatula to flip a pancake |\n\n## Grasp Planning\n\nGrasp planning determines where and how to grip an object.\n\n**Analytical approaches** compute grasps using geometric and physical analysis:\n- Force closure: find contact points that resist any external wrench\n- Form closure: the object is geometrically constrained by the fingers\n\n**Learned approaches** use neural networks to predict grasp success:\n- **GraspNet**: Predicts 6-DoF grasp poses from point clouds\n- **Contact-GraspNet**: Generates grasps conditioned on semantic segmentation\n- Trained on large-scale datasets of simulated grasps with success labels\n\nLearned approaches handle novel objects and clutter far better than analytical methods.\n\n## Dexterous Hands\n\nHigh-DoF (degrees of freedom) robotic hands open up manipulation capabilities impossible with parallel-jaw grippers:\n\n- **Shadow Hand**: 20 DoF, 24 joints, anthropomorphic — the reference research platform\n- **Allegro Hand**: 16 DoF, more robust and affordable\n- **LEAP Hand**: Open-source, 3D-printable, low-cost dexterous hand\n\nControlling a 20-DoF hand is a massive challenge: the action space is high-dimensional, contact dynamics are complex, and tactile feedback is essential.\n\nRL in simulation has proven remarkably effective. OpenAI's work on **in-hand cube rotation** with a Shadow Hand — trained entirely in simulation with domain randomization — was a landmark demonstration.\n\n## Tactile Sensing\n\nVision tells the robot *where* to grasp; **tactile sensing** tells it *how hard* and *how well*:\n\n- **GelSight**: A camera behind a soft gel membrane captures high-resolution contact geometry and force distribution\n- **BioTac**: Multi-modal fingertip sensor measuring pressure, vibration, and temperature\n- **Capacitive arrays**: Flexible pressure-sensing skins that wrap around fingers or robot bodies\n\nTactile feedback enables **contact-rich manipulation** — tasks like inserting a USB plug, threading a needle, or feeling for a key in a pocket that are impossible with vision alone.\n\n## In-Hand Manipulation\n\n**In-hand manipulation** is the ability to reposition, reorient, or reconfigure an object using only finger motions — without putting it down. Examples:\n\n- Rotating a cube to a target orientation\n- Repositioning a pen for writing\n- Flipping a tool to use a different end\n\nThis requires precise multi-finger coordination, real-time tactile feedback, and robust contact modeling. Recent RL successes (trained in Isaac Gym with domain randomization) have shown policies that transfer to real dexterous hands.\n\n## Key Takeaways\n\n- Manipulation ranges from simple grasping to dexterous in-hand control\n- Learned grasp planning outperforms analytical methods on novel objects\n- High-DoF dexterous hands are controlled effectively using RL in simulation\n- Tactile sensing is essential for contact-rich tasks beyond simple pick-and-place\n- Deformable objects and tool use remain open challenges at the frontier\n",
          "summary": "Dexterous manipulation encompasses grasp planning, multi-fingered hand control, tactile sensing, and contact-rich tasks, with RL in simulation enabling remarkable capabilities like in-hand object rotation.",
          "concepts": [
            "grasp planning",
            "dexterous manipulation",
            "tactile sensing",
            "in-hand manipulation",
            "degrees of freedom",
            "contact-rich manipulation",
            "GelSight"
          ],
          "youtube_id": null,
          "video_title": null,
